- Installs the package(s) specified, along with any dependencies.
apt-get install package-name(s) 

- Removes the package(s) specified, but does not remove dependencies.
apt-get remove package-name(s) 

- Removes any orphaned dependencies, meaning those that remain installed but are no longer required.
apt-get autoremove 

- Removes downloaded package files (.deb) for software that is already installed.
apt-get clean 

- Combines the functions of remove and clean for a specific package, as well as configuration files.
apt-get purge package-name(s) 

- Reads the /etc/apt/sources.list file and updates the systemâ€™s database of packages available for installation. Run this after changing sources.list.
apt-get update 

- Upgrades all packages if there are updates available. Run this after running apt-get update.
apt-get upgrade 


- If you know the name of a piece of software but apt-get install fails or points to the wrong software, this looks for other possible names.
apt-cache search package-name(s) 

- Shows dependency information, version numbers and a basic description of the package.
apt-cache show package-name(s) 

- Lists the packages that the specified packages depends upon in a tree. These are the packages that will be installed with the apt-get install command.
apt-cache depends package-name(s) 

- Outputs a list of packages that depend upon the specified package. This list can often be rather long, so it is best to pipe its output through a command, like less.
apt-cache rdepends package-name(s) 

- Generates a list of the currently installed packages on your system. This list is often rather long, so it is best to pipe its output through a program, like less, or direct the output to a text file.
apt-cache pkgnames 
